      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":7,\"target_duration_minutes\":43,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":370,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":370,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start very relaxed, just getting the legs moving. No pressure to hit pace yet.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":33,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":370,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a comfortable conversational pace. You should be able to speak in full sentences throughout.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease off the pace, let your heart rate come down naturally.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"5 minutes of easy walking or very slow jogging before you settle into your easy pace.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Finish with 5 minutes of easy walking and light dynamic stretching — hip circles, leg swings, and calf raises.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This is your foundational aerobic run for the week. The goal is purely aerobic development — building the capillary network and mitochondrial density that will underpin your half marathon fitness. Keep it genuinely easy. Your easy pace range is 5:50–6:27/km, so aim for the middle to slower end today. If it feels almost too easy, that's exactly right.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Lactate Threshold Cruise Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":58,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":370,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":290,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jogging warmup. Include 4 x 20-second strides in the final 3 minutes to prime your legs before threshold work.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":290,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First cruise interval at threshold pace (4:50/km). This should feel comfortably hard — you can speak a word or two but not hold a conversation.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Very easy jog recovery between cruise intervals. Keep moving — don't stop.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":290,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Second cruise interval. Maintain the same effort as the first — resist the urge to push harder.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jog recovery.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":290,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Third and final cruise interval. Focus on form — tall posture, relaxed shoulders, quick cadence.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":14,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jog cooldown. Let your breathing fully recover before you stop.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"12 minutes easy jogging, finishing with 4 short strides of about 20 seconds each to wake up your fast-twitch fibers before threshold work.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"14 minutes easy jogging followed by 5 minutes of static stretching — quads, hamstrings, hip flexors, and calves. Pay particular attention to your IT band given your history.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Cruise intervals are the cornerstone of half marathon preparation. Three 10-minute reps at threshold pace (4:50/km) with short recoveries trains your body to clear lactate more efficiently — which is exactly what you need to sustain pace over 21.1 km. Your previous tempo work showed a solid 4km at threshold, so we're extending the total threshold volume here. The short 2-minute recoveries keep the stimulus continuous without letting you fully recover, which is the key adaptation driver.\",\"perceived_effort\":7},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Recovery\",\"title\":\"Active Recovery Run\",\"target_distance_km\":5,\"target_duration_minutes\":33,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":387,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":387,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":33,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Keep this genuinely easy — slower end of your easy range or even slower. This is about blood flow and recovery, not fitness building.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No formal warmup needed — just start very slowly and ease in.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Finish with 5–10 minutes of gentle stretching, focusing on your IT band, hip flexors, and glutes. A foam roller on your lateral quad and IT band would be a great addition today.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"The day after a threshold session, your body is doing repair work. This short, easy run accelerates that process by increasing blood flow to the muscles without adding meaningful stress. Think of it as active recovery rather than training. The pace should feel almost embarrassingly slow — that's the point. This is also a good day to check in with how your IT band is feeling after yesterday's harder effort.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"workout_type\":\"Interval\",\"title\":\"VO2max Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":9,\"target_duration_minutes\":55,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":370,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":271,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jogging warmup. Include 4–6 x 20-second strides in the final 4 minutes to prime your neuromuscular system.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":271,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"5 x 3-minute intervals at interval pace (4:31/km). This is hard — a 9 or 9.5 out of 10 effort. You should not be able to speak more than a single word. Run tall, drive your arms, stay controlled.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"2-minute easy jog recovery between each interval. Keep moving — walking is fine if needed but try to jog slowly.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jog cooldown. Take your time here — let your heart rate come all the way down.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"15 minutes easy jogging with 4–6 x 20-second strides near the end. Your body needs to be genuinely warm before interval work.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"15 minutes easy jogging followed by thorough stretching. Given your IT band history, include lateral hip and glute stretches — clamshells and pigeon pose are excellent here.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"VO2max intervals are the most physiologically demanding session of the week, and they serve a specific purpose: raising your aerobic ceiling. By running at 4:31/km — your interval pace — you're pushing your cardiovascular system to work at or near its maximum oxygen uptake, which over time raises the ceiling of what your aerobic system can sustain. For a 1:45 half marathon goal (roughly 5:00/km), a higher VO2max gives you more headroom. Five 3-minute reps is a manageable starting volume that we can build on in coming weeks. The key is hitting the pace — not going faster.\",\"perceived_effort\":8},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Aerobic Long Run\",\"target_distance_km\":15,\"target_duration_minutes\":97,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":387,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":387,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":7,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":400,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start very easy for the first 7 minutes. Your body needs time to warm up, especially on a long run.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":83,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a steady easy pace — aim for 6:20–6:27/km. Conversational throughout. If you feel good in the final 20 minutes, you can drift toward the faster end of easy (around 6:00/km), but only if it feels natural.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":7,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":400,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease off in the final 7 minutes. Arrive at the finish feeling like you could have kept going.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start slower than you think you need to. The first kilometre should feel almost too easy — your aerobic system needs 10–15 minutes to fully engage.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"After finishing, walk for 5 minutes before stopping completely. Follow with thorough stretching — IT band, hip flexors, calves, and hamstrings. Hydrate and refuel within 30 minutes.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"The long run is the single most important session of the week for half marathon preparation. At 15 km, we're taking a modest step up from your recent 14 km long run — well within the 10% progression guideline. The physiological benefits are significant: increased glycogen storage, improved fat oxidation, greater mitochondrial density, and enhanced running economy at race pace. Keep the pace genuinely easy (6:20–6:27/km). The adaptation comes from time on feet, not pace. Given your 75-minute session cap, 15 km at easy pace fits comfortably within that window. We'll build this gradually toward 18–20 km over the coming weeks as your race approaches.\",\"perceived_effort\":5}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
